The menu of an obese child: it doesn’t eat breakfast and eats sausage for dinner
More than one-third of children aged 9 to 13 have problems with obesity, with 9 percent of all students and 5 percent of all children being overweight.
Recent surveys have shown that obese children are mostly from families with unhealthy lifestyles.
This shows once again how important for the healthy development of a person is the environment in which he grows up and the examples that surround him.
On the tables of obese children, sausages are up to half more often on the table than in families where normal-weight children live.
More than 19 percent of overweight children had fries for dinner on the eve of the education campaign under the motto "obesity is no coincidence".
In families with little kids, sports is not exactly one of the favorite occupations, but it also affects the majority of today's students - only 15 percent responded that their parents find time for active exercise at least once a week.
Survey of 900 children
The survey took place last year at the end of the school year, surveying almost 900 children from primary schools across the Czech Republic.
This was already the second year of the action "Obesity is not a coincidence", which is supported by the General Health Insurance and the company Unilever.
So far, more than 12 thousand students from 4th and 8th grades have participated in the project.
Unhealthy diet and lack of exercise in the family are decisive factors that are responsible for the frighteningly increasing number of overweight or even obese children.
"For example, only half of the children surveyed cited eating breakfast-second breakfast-lunch-vesper evening bread five times a day -- one of the main prerequisites for a healthy diet," said one of the survey's findings.
No breakfast and sausage for dinner
Experts point out that even relative small things, such as the regular breakfast time of the family, are important for the healthy development of a child.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23 percent of the families of the students eat breakfast.
And - in most families, everyone eats breakfast on their own.
Worst was the finding that breakfast is not eaten at all in every tenth family.
Breakfast is considered to be the cornerstone of a healthy daily diet.
Among other things, the survey test revealed that in the families of overweight children, unhealthy fries are consumed much more often.
And almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet sodas every day (70 percent)
While more than 40 percent of children surveyed do sports, only less than half of their parents do – namely only 15 percent.
Create your own menu
Another part of the survey enabled selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to create their own meal plan based on the choices offered by appetite and opinion.
"What Czech children between 12 and 15 prefer in terms of nutrition is far from the ideal of a healthy diet.
Among her favorite foods were many meals, meat dishes and of course sweets.
"Alarming is above all the great popularity of sweet sodas," the final report to this survey emphasizes.
At lunch, i.e. the main dish, pastas prevailed just before poultry.
The children almost did not like legumes and also the popularity of fish and vegetable dishes as lunch was very low.
Return to Health
At the same time, however, the survey also showed that the children are quite willing to change their eating habits when they get the right information.
"In the control group of survey respondents who completed the questionnaire after completing the enlightening talk "Obesity is not a coincidence", in many cases, a significant shift in preferences towards principles of healthy eating was noted," the project's results stated.
This was eye-catching, for example, with the sweet limes, where many children began to give priority to ordinary water.
The children also crossed in the questionnaire much more often poultry or fish as the main dish of the day and were willing to eat less dumplings or sweet foods.
Professionals claim - a stylist must also be a good psychologist
In the introductory article about how stylists learn, I had a bit of memorized that this was a bit too much stuff for the beginning.
