V Need for Speed: "The Run" - the illegal race across America
Testimonial
The original carefree ride is made by a series of completely avoidable, dilettante mistakes to the routine ride to the early shift.
Although the ambitions were largely met, what good is it if obviously no one wanted to do a little more?
Even before he came to the counter, the new part with the subtitle "The Run" aroused high expectations.
After all, he promised to move the already aged game series "Need for Speed" once again to a new dimension and in the playable demonstration examples, he didn't seem to be just one of many action racing games.
We were also curious about the fitting passages in which the main protagonist gets out of the car and continues on foot.
But as you are already used to with NFS, in the end, much is different than you expected.
Sure - potentially it's quite decent arcade races, but overall, the game is narrowed down by some superfluous mistakes that have been present in this series for more or less a few years.
So they are actually no longer mistakes, but rather signs of a basically incomprehensible laziness of the game developers.
The adventure begins very well.
For the first time, you are introduced to the story, whose main character Jack has certain problems of personal character; the only solution seems to be to participate in an illegal race across America.
In San Francisco, on the west coast, you get on the steering wheel - with the task of being the first to be in New York.
The basic idea includes a whole series of interesting elements.
The entire route is divided into ten stages and more than fifty individual races.
This means that each race is held on a different track and that the individual stages take place in a different, sufficiently different and interesting environment.
You don’t have the impression for a moment that the game would offer the same thing over and over again.
Some environments are still very pretty to look at, although the technical level of the graphics does not go beyond that of the previous parts of the series.
So nothing world-moving.
But the drive through the desert, through autumnal landscape or high up through deeply snowed landscape looks visually very pleasant.
Occasionally, untypical elements bring a little variety to the individual races.
In the desert, for example, one is surprised by a desert storm that severely restricts the view.
In the mountains, you have to be careful that you are not spilled by an avalanche.
By the way, the individual races are built in fairly well one after the other.
Only a few, but they are enough.
For a while you try to overtake the prescribed number of opponents (in principle, a classic race), then you have time to catch up (classic race against the stopwatch), then you expect a personal duel with a single opponent.
And the police are also involved, who want to mess up the whole thing.
A novelty is passages in which Jack leaves the car.
It’s more about certain interactive animations where Jack escapes from someone and where the player has to help him by pressing the right button at the right moment.
So nothing complicated.
However, it is surprising that there are far fewer such passages in the game than you would expect (concretely only three).
Ultimately, this is more to the advantage of the thing, because so at least this element has no chance of becoming boring - it belongs in the context of the above mentioned elements that make the game more varied.
The driving model walks in the footsteps of the previous parts.
That is, from today’s point of view, it does not tear down trees, on the other hand, you could not say it would be bad.
If you are looking for realistic simulations, you have to look elsewhere.
But an action-packed racing continues to do justice to the local driving model, although you could find better in the competition.
Until then, everything is fine.
Real problems only appear after a while.
In contrast to the driving model, the collision model is not entirely OK.
It is unlikely that a game of this kind will calculate complicated deformations and collisions, but if you have practically no idea how the car behaves before an impact on any object, then obviously everything is not fine.
Typical example: When overtaking or passing by oncoming cars, in some places you "strike" the other cars only slightly, but in other, almost identical situations you get into slingshot and turn wild pirouettes.
Or the carriage will go to scrap.
Thanks to the restart system, it doesn't matter anymore, but it's annoying.
The restarts are solved in this way: if you have total damage or land far away from the track, then you throw the game back to the last point of the track.
Only - in each race you only have five restarts.
Once you’ve exhausted it, everything starts from scratch.
So the restarts are more like a tool, in case something doesn’t work, but you shouldn’t rely on it.
But sometimes even the restart doesn’t help, there’s nothing else that helps but to learn the critical section from the mind.
It is extremely unpleasant that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, you have to go through some curves in a very specific way, otherwise you simply do not pass through.
Elsewhere, you always encounter "civil" cars in the same configuration, whether you are first or fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is especially annoying in situations when you see the opponent passing by two cars in front of you, but until you arrive there, the cars are already in such a position that you have to drive them around or brake.
And it doesn’t matter when you arrive there, because everything is designed so that it always comes close to your nose to this situation.
The counterparts have even more advantages.
Throughout the game there are a few places where you are always overtaken by the same opponent at the same place and again here without regard to the timing.
The most insane is at the end of the game on the long bridge that you pass in the opposite direction.
The counterpart must obviously overtake you here on the devil come out.
And if he is already in front of you, then of course he takes your sight, so that you initially drive your own car a few times in Klump.
Sure - you just want to make the game more exciting and exciting, but this intention is so clear that it quickly spoils the joy of the game.
And that’s a pity, because despite the simpler driving model, the game is overall quite entertaining and in some places so action-packed that you almost don’t know where your head is.
And in principle, it doesn't matter what "blame" is on it - the concept with fifty unique routes, the arrangement of the races in a way that no boredom can come up, or something completely different...
An unusual idea is also the change of car during the races.
You should not overlook the gas stations on the route, because it is here that you can change the car, although in most cases the car that you currently have is enough.
The cars are divided into three categories.
The sports cars are well suited for the urban areas, the strong American limousines for the straight highways and exotic super sports cars for the technical rides, for example on the serpentines in the mountains.
Hand in hand with the mode of the game history goes the task mode (challenges) - i.e. the races in the individual locations you know from the story.
Here, there are not only medals, but also experience points to win for your own profile, which is common for the tasks (challenges) and history.
In order to get to the higher driver level, different items must be unlocked: from the car to the backgrounds for the profile.
This is simultaneously connected to the online function Autolog, which compares its own results with those of other players and also provides further collective functions.
One of the other incomprehensible carvings is a situation in the last race of history.
Here you get by car into a subway tunnel (for my sake), where you can rest in the dark on the rails for a long time (for my sake).
On the speedometer, figures look between 150 and 200 km/h (for my sake), but there comes suddenly a subway from behind and drives an uncompromising to scrap.
In our editorial team we will probably argue for a long time about whether this was a blackout of the game designers or whether the authors think we are so stupid.
The technical side is nothing overwhelming but at least the overall visual impression is quite appealing in most cases and even brilliant here and there.
It is all the more annoying that at some exciting moments the refresh rate slows down and this is sometimes quite dramatic.
However, this applies in particular to accidents involving a larger number of parties, where a continuous FPS is of no use anyway.
The sound playback is OK and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to address as broad a scale as possible rather young audiences, a soundtrack a lá "something" was created - but who buys such a game because of the music?!
Need for Speed: The Run: The Run: Need for Speed: The Run: The Run
If the game wasn’t diminished by the above-mentioned totally unnecessary mistakes, we could have claimed with the tone of the chest that The Run is the best piece by NFS in recent years.
But that’s how the game seems to be somehow unfinished.
It’s a great pleasure in itself, but you should be prepared to make these mistakes with the power of airport headlights.
