Innovator IBM enters the second century of its existence
If you wanted to look for a suitable word that most accurately characterizes IBM's strategy, this would probably be the word "longevity".
For the general public, IBM is synonymous with technological revolution, known as a modern company, although a century has passed since it was founded.
The foundation for this longevity was already laid by their first boss - the visionary Thomas J. Watson sen.
Already he represented the slogan, countless worldwide problems could easily be solved if people were willing to think a bit.
His slogan "Think!" thus became the hallmark of the future giant's life (and at the same time the title of the company's in-house magazine, which began to be published at IBM in 1935).
This was also the basis of Watsen’s well-prepared corporate culture.
"For us from IBM, this long-term thinking means a continuous movement towards the future.
IBM survived and was successful for a whole century because it remained true to its principles and did not shy away from changing everything else around it.
This allowed us to transform technology, business and society in the course of our first century.
We hope to achieve even more in the next hundred years,” said Samuel J. Palmisano, today’s director of the company on the occasion of the anniversary.
Well-thought-out system
As early as the 1930s, Watson had social care for his employees - in a similar way to the entrepreneur Ba<0xC5><0xA5>a in Czechoslovakia: the IBM people had paid leave as one of the first American employees, an insurance policy by the entrepreneur plus elegant uniforms as work clothes and a well-thought-out pay system for the best newcomers and merchants.
IBM’s long-term relationships with its customers are equally well-informed.
The company was brilliant in talent promotion from the start – being one of the first companies in the world to eliminate discrimination – and was able to choose accordingly.
In line with this anti-discrimination strategy, the current plan is also that Palmisan at the head of IBM will be replaced by a woman next year – Virginia Rometty.
