In recent years, IBM has been making so-called online brainstormings, from which many future strategies and innovations grow.
No wonder - there are enough ideas, after all, almost half a million people are employed in the company.
An institution with a good reputation
Their unwavering position in business guarantees the company a strong image, both internally and externally.
"From the beginning, IBM had the concept of an institution rather than a mere technology company," said Economist, Harvard Business School professor and author of a book about IBM, Rosabeth Moss Kanter.
“IBM is not a technology company, but a company that helps solve business problems using technology,” added George Colony of consulting firm Forrester Research.
As the company itself emphasizes, it is a difference to be only present in the market or to shape it directly through this presence.
IBM – called “Big Blue” in the states of its logo because of its family history – has grown into one of the largest companies in the world in a century.
It is one of the most versatile technology companies ever – IBM develops hardware and software, infrastructure, hosting and consulting services in an incredible range of products – from servers to nanotechnology.
Of all American technology companies, IBM holds the most patents, and five of its employees have already been awarded the Nobel Prize.
His most famous inventions include, for example, ATMs, credit cards, financial swap, barcode or even the floppy disk.
At around $220 billion in market capitalization, IBM was the second-largest technology company this year (equal to Apple), overtaking Microsoft for the first time since 1996.
The look ahead
Not all products and innovations met the taste of today's customers - unhappy were, for example, the attempt with its own operating system OS/2, the online service Prodigy or even the computers IBM PC jr.
“Business is based on moving forward, so you can’t be emotionally bound to the past,” says Samuel J. Palmisano.
That’s why IBM has no problem building its foundations on different platforms – and if they don’t work, they’ll leave again.
In contrast to the opponent Microsoft, which in principle with its operating system Windows stands and falls.
Promising technologies
In IBM’s profits, services, software and hardware account for one-fifth of the total.
In 1990, hardware was the most represented, with a share of more than fifty per cent.
Since 2000, IBM has sold $15 billion worth of profitable assets, but at the same time invested $58 billion in the purchase of future-proof technologies.
IBM continues to invest in these investments after 2008, when the modern financial crisis swept the world for the first time like a storm.
Here too, IBM remained faithful to the legacy of its first boss, Thomas J. Watson, who increased his investment volume in the middle of the Great Depression.
So far, it seems that the company IBM survives today’s crisis unharmed.
Since 2008, the value of IBM’s shares has risen by 120% in a rocket-like manner, and the company’s net profit is growing continuously.
IBM’s corporate slogan is: everything can be changed – except the values.
