IBM History: From Cheese Cutter to Spaceflight
Founded one hundred years ago in New York, IBM (International Business Machines) had a rather complicated name at first - Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It was not until 1924 that it took over the name IBM – originally a brand name for a subsidiary in Canada and South America.
IBM was founded by the merger of four companies whose history dates back to the 1980s.
They possessed technologies such as the famous punctuation card clocks to record the start and end of work.
The architect of this new company was Charles Ranlett Flint, who also chaired the Supervisory Board until 1930.
And it was Flint who hired the head of the competition company Thomas J. Watson to help him manage the company.
This leader then even eclipsed the founders of IBM – based on Watson’s ideas to this day, the company’s invincible culture and identity.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, began manufacturing and distributing all sorts of machines for trade - from sausage and cheese cutters to cash registers.
In the first four decades of running the company, Watson doubled his revenues to $9 million and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so essential to the company that he sat in the chair for forty years, only then was he replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, IBM technicians and computers helped NASA guide flights into space – to Mercury and Saturn, and in 1969 also the famous human flight to the moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first computer family with the same computing architecture - the IBM System/360 series.
A classic PC, which set the computer standard at the time, was launched in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand, it bought the consultant share of the company PricewaterhouseCoopers and thus entered fully into the business of consulting and high-value services.
The strategy that IBM has been paying off over the last three years is the “Smart Planet” concept.
It embodies the intention to use technologies wisely in previously unplanned areas, e.g. to improve the situation in transport and urban administration.
In the retail sector, IBM recently launched the “Smarter Commerce” platform to help retailers guide the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
As early as 1932, IBM established a branch in the then Czechoslovakia - the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM <0xC4><0x8C>R also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Central and Eastern European Headquarters is located in Prague, where there is also a world-class top-level research team that deals with voice recognition technology.
