Development of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five approved state travel agencies in the former <0xC4><0x8C>SSR: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
The travel agencies at the time mainly sold only travel to the socialist Eastern Bloc countries, in the West then only selected ones were allowed.
And so Czech tourists travelled to the Baltic Sea (in the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the peninsula of Crimea on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when you were also allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia embarked on a pro-Western course and therefore travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that not even citizens of the Eastern Bloc (i.e. also the Czechoslovaks) were allowed to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of the <0xC4><0x8C>SSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, he would need a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual travel would not be possible.
Even then, the travel agencies also offered travel to the West, but then you had to accept huge snakes or also spend the night in a sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
Even so, things had not gone well.
The so-called foreign exchange commitment - the condition for a trip to the West - was only given to "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so without the foreign exchange commitment it would have been impossible to raise the necessary funds (western currency) for a trip to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs therefore spent their holidays inland, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and datches - a habit that continues to this day.
The velvet revolution of 1989 was followed by a travel revolution of the Czechs.
While until 1989 a holiday in the GDR or in Bulgaria was the measure of all things, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their holidays abroad in countries all over the world.
A huge paradox, of which we are no longer aware today, is the fact that you could not travel to the currently most popular holiday country of the Czechs - Croatia until 1989, because it was part of the then Yugoslavia.
Right from the beginning of the 90s of the last century, the foreign exchange obligation in the neighbouring Western European countries was abolished, which caused a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and to Germany.
The Czechoslovaks simply couldn’t get enough of their travels to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to be there for at least a few days.
For example, the Czech holidaymakers slept in the tent in the park when traveling to Paris, because who would have had the money for accommodation in a hotel or in a guesthouse at the time.
A typical feature of Czech trips abroad at the time was a trunk packed with canned food, beer and permanent sausage etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech crown - after decades, our tourists were finally able to buy the Western currency freely.
Our level of living and, as a result, the average salaries increased, which led to another important moment in 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies began to regularly prepare charter flights after 1997, making air travel incredibly affordable compared to the past, thanks to the ability to negotiate volume discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the United States, had already exchange-free payments with all the highly developed countries of the world, making travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-velvety" travel came in 2000, when, thanks to the high demand, the first direct charter flight was completed to an exotic country - to Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights with Czech passengers have been flying to far-away sunny countries every year; this year, twelve exotic destinations are flying directly from the Czech Republic.
About 100 thousand Czechs travel to exotic countries every year!
Another significant moment in the epoch that marked our “post-revolutionary” development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most advanced countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs spent for the first time more than half of their holiday abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history spent more than 15 thousand CZK per capita on a single holiday stay, including the costs at the resort.
