If Iris Meder went on a search trip in the past year and a half, one thing in her luggage should not be missed: her swimsuit.
Laying on the water, she looked high in elaborately designed domes, she swam towards marble puddles waiting for her at the edge of the basin, and marveled at meticulously restored Art Nouveau swimming pools.
If she liked a bath, she quickly recorded it in her notebook - with interesting details about the construction and history of the building.
The architectural historian Meder explored more than 200 swimming pools in this way - and now presents them in her recently published book "Badefreuden": Volksschwimmhallen in Munich, historic bathing palaces in the Black Forest, "Hardcore concrete buildings" in Taunus.
Through 13 countries she led her "travel to the most extraordinary baths in Central Europe": in addition to Germany, Austria and Switzerland, she visited places in Italy, France, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania, Poland - and one city in Luxembourg, Serbia and Croatia.
The 46-year-old German is a true bathing enthusiast.
She doesn't have much to do with sports, says Meder - only in the water it is different.
It’s annoying that swimmers have to accept blue tiles and chlorine stench, while joggers can breathe in the enchanting scent of spruce forests or listen to the cheerful birdsong in the park.
“I wondered one day why swimming pools always have to be so ugly,” says Meder, who lives in Vienna.
"So I started collecting beautiful baths."
Water surface doubles architecture
Spasms in the spring basin and essential sauna oils - the wellness factor in baths is therefore so large, because all the senses are served, according to Meder.
And if the builders have made an effort, swimming pools can be a real eye-catcher: "Instead of a floor, you have a water surface in bathrooms."
"It is transparent on the one hand, but on the other hand reflects the beauty of the whole building."
Everything doubles visually: high vaults, colorful tiles, springboards.
On 190 pages, the small-format picture book "Badefreuden" conveys information about the architectural and cultural history of historic wellness oases - but above all, it makes you want to jump into the blue.
Notable specimens were discovered by the pool collector Meder during her research in Hungary.
In addition to magnificent spas such as the 100-year-old Széchenyi Bath in Budapest, it found a nitrate-containing water in a quaint karst cave (cave bath in Miskolc-Tapolca) as well as a thermal bath, whose basins are filled with alkaline water and are located in a bottle-shaped building (Városi Termálfürdö in Jásber).
Spectacular views, on the other hand, are offered by many heated outdoor swimming pools in Switzerland and Austria: while the Zurich rooftop swimming pool has the whole city in mind, you can look at the snow-covered Arlberg in the outdoor swimming pool of a bath in St. Anton - and: In the steam room there is a window from which you can observe the activity on the ski slopes.
Perhaps the most extraordinary pool design awaits bathers in Längenfeld: The Aquadome <0xC3><0x96>tztal looks like a UFO just landed in the Alps.
From three bowls open upwards, it steams in winter, while in the background the mountains of the <0xC3><0x96>tztal project into the sky.
Alhambra in the Black Forest
Not in every swimming pool, pool collector Meder put the smell of chlorine in her nose.
Many thermal baths smell like sulphur, in the <0xC3><0x81>rpád bath in the Hungarian town of Békescsaba it smells so strongly of fuel oil that you hardly think you landed in a health bath.
The smell comes from the alkali hydrogen carbonate-containing healing water, which is almost black and whose silt sticks to the skin as soon as you slide into the pelvis - a wellness experience of a special kind.
In one place, however, Iris Meder was also disappointed in her search for beautiful bathing places: When she wanted to visit the outdoor and sunbathing pool in the Czech town of Luhatschowitz, she found a confined terrain.
The bathroom, designed by the architect Du<0xC5><0xA1>an Jurkovic in 1902, has since been closed.
As Meder glanced through the weathered windows of the red-white-yellow Art Nouveau building, she saw weeds growing between the tiles.
On the other hand, the decay has been counteracted in a magical swimming pool in the Black Forest: the Palais Thermal in Bad Wildbad.
