The 21st House in Vienna
The relocated pavilion
By Ingeborg Wiensowski
An architectural history with highs, lows and happy end: The Austrian World Exhibition Pavilion of Brussels won prizes in 1958, became a museum in Vienna, stood empty and disappeared.
It is now reopened as an exhibition house.
If modern post-war architecture, clear shapes, glass halls, bold swings and new building materials typical of the belief in technological progress are infused with, then the Austrian pavilion of architect Karl Schwanzer is a striking and famous example for the 1958 Brussels World Exhibition.
Schwanzer’s pavilion was awarded the Grand Prix d’Architecture for its lightweight and floating steel-glass construction.
The building is still considered to be a milestone of contemporary architecture.
He made the architect so famous that he also built the pavilion at the next Austrian World Exhibition.
With his legendary BMW four-cylinder house plus bowl-like accessory building in Munich, he finally became internationally famous in 1973.
Its pavilion, which was planned as a temporary exhibition building, had been erected after the World Exhibition in the Swiss Garden at the South Station in Vienna, and rebuilt in 1962 and opened a museum of the 20th century - the "20's house" was called it.
However, the building was neither spatially nor technically suitable as a museum - no walls for hanging art, no good climate.
Nevertheless, it was used until contemporary art in Vienna got a new house.
Since 2001, the building was empty and came down more and more.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has rebuilt the pavilion, it is now called "21er Haus" and will be used as a museum of contemporary art in the future.
On Tuesday evening, the Museum Belvedere, to which the house belongs, opens its first exhibition there - a success in every respect.
Agnes Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian Gallery Belvedere in 2007.
Husslein-Arco, an art historian with a considerable career, among other things, in her youth as an art runner, later at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the Museum der Moderne Salzburg, insisted on the conversion of politicians and conservationists, she procured public funds and private sponsorship funds and determined the use.
In addition to contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba were to be exhibited by the foundation of the same name, a café and a bookstore were to exist, and an office building had to be built for this purpose.
Strict supervision, small budget
For the performance, Krischanitz was the ideal occupation.
Not only because he had sensitively rebuilt and expanded Joseph Olbrich’s Secession in Vienna and won the competition, but because he studied at Schwanzer at the Technical University of Vienna and the pavilion was for him a “very important place”, where he had looked at the exhibitions “almost every weekend”.
He knew the original design, and he knew the problems of the building, which already lost its generosity and ease during its transfer to Vienna and its reuse.
There were far bigger problems with the current renovation: The building was "an energy shooter," says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass facade were replaced, glass fiber-reinforced insulating glass was used and the glass roof was replaced by special safety glass.
Cold bridge steel beams have been reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled ceilings have been refurbished.
Two basements made room for the new use, a lowered light pit between the house and the road provides the exposure, a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building, but still the light tail pavilion.
The original exterior doors have remained, the house is painted in old red-brown anti-rust shade.
The cinema is exactly as it used to be.
And all this under the strict supervision of the monument authority and with a small budget.
"Often a material had to be found that is good and cheap and also liked by the monument protection office," says Krischanitz, pointing to a rugged floor in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and conversions, the building has remained flexible and lightweight.
The pavilion “was coming from Brussels,” Krischanitz recently said, a typical “drop-in-the-city story.”
Such an architecture is "always in the wrong place" and still wants to "raise a real consciousness".
In this case, however, the 21st-century house is not in the wrong place, because it has been an urban development success: Around the Swiss garden, the completely newly planned "Hauptbahnhofsquartier", with offices and residential buildings, is being built.
And another luck might happen: the 21st house could get reinforcements from another Krischanitz building, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg bought the Berliner Temporäre Kunsthalle, and as you can hear, she is already negotiating with the city for a neighborhood location in the Swiss garden.
