On the one hand, UBS is huge – until recently it was the largest wealth manager in the world – and on the other hand, it has been sliding from one scandal to the next for years.
Nothing, it seems, is spared the once so proud Swiss bank.
It started in the financial crisis.
Until 2007, UBS had an excellent reputation.
The image of the silent and solid, but also exhausted Swiss asset manager had combined it with ambitious goals: it wanted to become a very big number in investment banking, too.
On the one hand, UBS managed $1.6 trillion more money from wealthy customers than any other bank in the world in 2007.
On the other hand, as an investment bank, she had advanced into the league of the largest banks in the world.
That made an impression.
The former banker and later long-time banking professor in Zurich, Hans Geiger, tells us: "I always presented UBS to my students as a model of a good bank at the time."
"From today's point of view, you ask yourself: How could I be so wrong?"
He was greatly mistaken.
In 2007, it became apparent for the first time that something went wrong at UBS.
In the middle of the year, CEO Peter Wuffli surprisingly resigned, who until then was considered a highly intellectual and equally brilliant banker.
A few months later, they knew why he had left.
The bank’s investment division had tangled up with subprime papers and had to write off billions.
To blame this, UBS announced a capital increase of CHF 13 billion.
In fact, it found investors, but ones that some people would have rumbled about until recently: an untransparent Asian sovereign fund from Singapore and an Arab sovereign fund that was so concealed that you didn’t even know its name.
But that was only the first blow.
It was worse in April 2008.
The bank had to announce new billion losses, CEO Marcel Ospel, the second best-paid board of directors in Switzerland, resigned in 2006.
In October 2008, the disaster followed: UBS faced the collapse in view of its misinvestment in the financial crisis and had to be rescued by the state.
The National Bank bought UBS for tens of billions of problematic securities, the Swiss Confederation gave six billion francs for a forced convertible bond, via which it could become co-owner of the bank.
The whole of Switzerland was shocked – for she noticed how dramatic it is for a small country to host such large banks.
Finally, the balance sheet total of UBS in 2007 was more than five times that of Switzerland’s economic output (see graph).
"Once again, we could not save UBS," says banking researcher Geiger.
The first disaster followed the second.
Already a few months later, UBS surrendered in the tax dispute with America and agreed to release the data of wealthy customers who may have stolen taxes with the help of the bank.
In addition, she agreed to a payment of $780 million – as a repayment of unjustified profits from these transactions, including a penalty charge.
UBS thus confessed more or less openly to having helped with tax evasion.
At the same time, she lost something that had always been her capital in the competition for rich customers: the nimbus of secrecy.
After the scandal, Swiss banking secrecy was no longer the same.
This was followed by the resignation of the CEO and Chairman of the Board of Directors.
And the exodus of customer money.
Within a few months, the bank had lost credibility in both key business areas: in investment banking due to misspeculation and in asset management through tax evasion aid.
And just as it got a little calmer again, just as you thought UBS would get it back, this unfortunate merchant story follows: A single merchant cheats 1.7 billion euros before the bank realizes that something is going wrong.
And it turns out: risk management in investment banking is obviously still not working.
"With the Adoboli case, one had to find that risk control has changed too little," says Martin Janssen, economist and financial professor at the University of Zurich's banking institute.
The CFO of a large German bank is also sure: "The problem with UBS is that it has no control over risk control."
It was precisely the idea of caution with which the Swiss bankers had long ago begun to become guardians of the great wealth of the world: not too great risks, but security for money - might even collapse the world beyond the Alpine Republic.
The vaults of Swiss banks had become a symbol of unwavering reliability like Lindt and Sprüngli for particularly noble chocolate.
The headquarters of UBS in Zurich still fits the stereotype of the sound Swiss private bank - it is only a bit larger.
Already the location is classic.
The bank is headquartered on Zurich’s Bahnhofstraße, which leads directly from the main railway station to Lake Zurich, which is surrounded by the snow-capped peaks of the Swiss mountains.
The buildings here are magnificent, the shop rentals are among the tallest in Europe.
Jewelers such as Tiffany's can be found here among Swiss traditional shops such as the Confiserie Sprüngli.
Swiss banks have resided here for centuries: from the National Bank to the Palace of Credit Suisse to elite private banks such as Julius Baer.
You enter the reception room of UBS through a heavy revolving door.
Inside the walls are marble-clad, in front of thick leather armchairs, next to the bench logo a large sign for the "safe".
UBS knows what the customer is looking for here: safety.
This idea of the Swiss bank has both Swiss major banks, UBS and Credit Suisse, but at some point displaced it - or betrayed it, as the boss of a small Swiss private bank finds.
He prefers not to read his name in the newspaper, after all, like all Swiss bankers, he also does business with the two major banks.
UBS had become much too big, he finds - especially in investment banking, where the Anglo-Saxons had also spread.
The Swiss have nothing more to say.
"And if so, they have long adapted to the customs of the Anglo-Saxons."
In fact, it was Anglo-Saxon investment banking that changed UBS, giving it high profits first, and then the debacle: No European financial institution has lost as much money in the subprime jungle as the Swiss big bank.
On October 15, 2008, the disaster became apparent.
"On that Wednesday, the government coalition of the small seven-million country decided the largest rescue operation in the history of their nation," writes author Lukas Hässig in his book "The UBS Crash."
Politicians approved up to CHF 68 billion or around EUR 45 billion to save the bank that is bankrupt.
How could this happen?
If you talk to Swiss bankers, they see the problem above all in the size of UBS.
In June 1998, two of the three major Swiss banks merged into a huge group.
A bank was created that was already too big for small Switzerland at the time of the merger - and continued to grow.
This helped the two different predecessor banks of UBS to complement themselves: a rich but sleepy bank with a focus on asset management in Zurich and a poorer but already more internationalized bank.
Suddenly, the internationalized investment bankers came in favour of a lot of money with which they could turn a huge wheel.
Two names are associated with this rise of UBS: Peter Wuffli, CEO of UBS from 2001 to 2007, and Marcel Ospel, then Chairman of the Board of Directors.
"I always thought Wuffli and Ospel were a dream team," says banking researcher Hans Geiger.
"Wuffli, the high intellectual, the modest who understands a lot of models and statistics, and Ospel, the belly man who has worked his way up from the bench to the top."
But Ospel ultimately relied on Wuffli.
And Wuffli probably made a decisive mistake in the end: "He thought his models were the reality," Geiger says.
“This is a tragic case.”
Tragic, perhaps.
Obviously, pride came before the fall.
Employees of UBS clearly remember the executive meetings at which CEO Wuffli repeatedly issued the same slogan: Goldman Sachs step down from the throne.
The American Bank was the most powerful investment bank in the world.
She led the League Tables, the rankings that documented the success of the banks of that time.
That’s where UBS wanted to go, to the top.
She had already taken a few steps.
In the foreign exchange business and in stock trading, she played at the top.
Business consultants who were commissioned, however, highlighted a weakness: In the international interest rate business, in the banking language "Fixed Income", there is a huge distance to the largest banks.
UBS has gaps in U.S. mortgage products.
To close this gap, UBS embarked on an adventure that almost cost her life.
Hungry for growth, both the bank itself and a hedge fund founded before it invested in American subprime investments.
It developed into a huge machine that packaged and passed on securities on American mortgage loans - but also kept risks on its own.
Even when other banks long ago sought the exit.
“Even in the summer of 2007, when the American real estate market was on fire, UBS bought there,” says banking expert Geiger.
So big the euphoria, so deep the case.
One manager after another had to go when the attempts to clean up were more difficult than expected.
Posts at UBS became the spinning seat and are still shaky to this day.
Whoever runs the big bank now has an almost impossible job.
He needs to find a strategy for a bank that has lost all the obvious business models.
Banking researcher Geiger already has an idea: Stop investment banking, focus on asset management, return to the Swiss roots.
The bank does not (yet) want to go that far.
But investment banking is expected to shrink sharply, so much is already clear.
Next Thursday, the new bank chief Sergio Ermotti wants to present his future strategy to the world.
The 51-year-old Italo-Swiss was actually only intended as a transitional solution when the bank surprisingly separated from its predecessor Grübel.
In the meantime, he has asserted himself: he should permanently manage the business of UBS, Züricher Bank announced on Tuesday.
Ermotti wants to bring the investment bank back to its mid-1990s status.
3500 posts will be deleted.
But that won't be enough.
UBS needs a vision.
Who's that?
What does she want to make money with?
These are the questions that Axel Weber is probably already asking himself.
So far, he has only said that he and his wife will be looking for an apartment in Zurich.
Next year.
