Intelligent crows spread in cities
In many places, seed crows are considered "problem birds": But the highly intelligent animals can no longer be expelled from the cities, experts claim.
Some like it, others want to get rid of it very quickly: crows have been part of the cityscape for centuries, but in many municipalities, residents' complaints about the dirt and noise of the animals are accumulating.
So far, no means of combating the "problem birds" is in sight.
Seed crows can no longer be taken out of the cities, experts said at the first crow symposium in East Frisian emptiness.
There, experts from the entire federal territory discussed possible ways out.
You are looking for alternatives in the cities
Conservationists also attributed the problems in cities to the displacement of the particularly protected seed crows: the use of chemicals in agriculture is increasingly destroying the traditional habitats.
Hunting, increasing cultivation and the felling of typical breeding trees made life difficult for birds.
Crows are under conservation.
Large colonies with more than 600 breeding pairs can be found in the Westphalian province of Soest, in the northwest, among others in Jever, Diepholz and Achim near Bremen, as well as in Leer.
In 2005, a controversial project for the mass killing of crows in the county had provided negative headlines.
Critics had described the capture of the animals in bird traps and the killing with clubs as particularly brutal.
"The normal displacement, the uglyness, does not help," said the city and landscape planner Werner Klöver from Leer.
Splashing away nests with water or cutting down trees often has unwanted consequences, also said environmental expert Manfred Kaiser from Lahr in Baden-Württemberg.
"The animals dodge, large colonies split up and spread elsewhere."
Disgrace is only conceivable as an exception in hospitals, retirement homes or schools.
"We have to live with them, we can't get them away."
Without the surrounding countryside, the problem in the cities could not be solved, Mayor Wolfgang Kellner from Leer said.
It is conceivable that a combination of the animals’ resentment from sensitive living areas and lure offerings would be possible in order to relocate them elsewhere.
"Infoboards instead of chainsaws" on the other hand, the psychologist and ethnologist Uta Maria Jürgens advertised for a completely different treatment of the animals: "A pimple in the face we can ultimately best bear with confidence."
Jürgens co-founded the Ascheberg Crow Teaching Path in Schleswig-Holstein, where signposts inform about the life of the highly intelligent seed crows.
The project is already being accepted by tourists.
Jürgens also had his own opinion on the criticism of the noise of the birds: "There is a lot of communication, they have a lot to say."
The intelligence and skill of the animals are legendary: Seed crows not only use tools to get a treat, but also produce their own tools as tools.
Behavioral researchers at the University of Cambridge recently tested on four seed crows how far the intelligence of the birds reaches.
In one experiment, the birds quickly learned that they had to collapse a scaffold with stones in order to reach a moth larva.
Without much training, they determinedly recognized what size and shape a stone must have to allow the platform to collapse.
In a second attempt, the clever crows had to solve a more tricky problem.
In a vertical cylinder, the researchers had placed a small bucket with a moth larva.
With the beak, the birds could not reach their prey.
However, the researchers had laid them pieces of wire.
From this, all four animals formed a hook, with the help of which they then fished the bucket on the handle from the tube.
Three of the four seed crows even succeeded immediately.
