Mission Ends, Congress Ready to Agree on Libya
In the end, it looks like Republicans and Democrats in Washington are already reaching agreement on the Libyan uprisings.
All that was needed was the success of the revolt, the arrest and assassination of longtime dictator Muammar Gaddafi and the end of American interference.
On Thursday, the Senate International Relations Committee will pass a resolution under the chairmanship of John Kerry (Massachusetts), along with Senators John McCain (Arizona) and Joseph I. Lieberman (Connecticut), praising Libya for the successful rebellion and the U.S. troops for their “bravery.”
"This resolution honors the brave people of Libya who have begun to rebuild their country," Kerry said.
"It is a confirmation of the support of its democratic efforts by two parties."
The language may sound innocent, but so far nothing has been easy in the Libyan debate.
This summer, lawmakers from both parties and the White House debated the wording of a series of resolutions approving or disapproving the role of the US military in NATO’s Libya mission.
In June, Kerry and McCain passed a resolution authorizing the restricted use of U.S. military forces in Libya.
The bill was rejected in the Senate by a broad fringe group of both parties and no vote was taken.
However, on the same day, the Senate passed the law, and the Chamber overturned a decision to cut funds for American operations in Libya.
As a result, the U.S. mission got into a kind of legislative purgatory — with a Congress that was upset enough to criticize Obama’s approach to the mission, but not angry enough to finally pull the floor under his feet.
Then the indecision of the Congress was overtaken by the events.
Tripoli fell among the Libyan rebels in August and Gaddafi was killed on October 20.
The NATO mission officially ended on October 31.
The Senate may be ready to act.
The resolution of the Committee on International Relations "congratulates the people of Libya for their tremendous courage and extraordinary endurance in their self-liberation" and "praises the men and women of the U.S. military and their coalition partners who support military operations to protect the people of Libya for their extraordinary courage and professionalism."
The resolution also reaffirms “the national interests of the United States in a successful and irrevocable transition of Libya to democracy.”
Will the new measures receive full support from the Foreign Relations Board or will they divide legislators, as the June law did?
The final version meets the opposition of Senator Richard G. Lugar (Indianapolis), the committee's top Republican.
Lugar’s spokesman said on Monday that he had not yet seen the final version of the new law.
According to the Capitol, it is up to the Senate to vote this week on a constitutional amendment that demands a balanced budget, a top priority in almost every congressional legislature of Republicans and some Democrats.
The measures under the leadership of Republican Bob Goodlatte (Virginia) will be the first constitutional amendment to the budget or any other area that is currently coming to a vote in the Senate or Congress.
Other legislators have so far unsuccessfully tried to bring their amendments to the vote, even though they have tried enough times.
Goodlatte’s amendment is just one of 68 constitutional amendments submitted to this Congress, covering a wide range of topics.
Some are double – the same law has been submitted to both Congress and the Senate – others are only slightly different from each other.
There are at least 15 versions of the balance sheet amendment in the Senate alone and another dozen that would "control federal spending".
Some of the laws are also identical, but they give their clients—especially beginners among Republicans who want to polish their resume—the opportunity to boast that they have “written” such a measure.
The Budget Control Act, passed in August, requires both the Senate and Congress to vote on a change in budget balance.
In March, 58 senators voted for a non-binding resolution supporting the idea of such a change.
In addition to the budget, some members want to limit the number of provisions that members of Congress can submit, while Republican José E. Serrano (New York) wants to lift the limitation on two presidential terms.
Republican Jesse L. Jackson (Illinois) has proposed a number of amendments that, among other things, guarantee the right to good education and health care.
An amendment prohibiting same-sex marriage is a recurring proposal, as is an amendment prohibiting the burning of flags.
Some legislators also want to allow the repeal of federal laws if two-thirds of the states reject them.
As eagerly as members propose changes, they move as quickly as they did in previous years.
In the 111th Congress, legislators presented 77 such amendments. in the 110th Congress 66.
The pace fades compared to that of the early 1990s, when members regularly proposed more than 150 changes every two years, according to figures provided by the Senate Library.
But they weren’t much more successful than today’s ones.
The last amendment to be added - the 27th - was ratified in 1992, but was actually proposed to Congress as early as 1789.
