“We found that it wasn’t hard to get to them,” says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recent report by the British idea factory DEMOS on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook’s hiding of personal data is so encyclopedic, Bartlett says, researchers simply need to use the site’s advertising tool to accurately determine their desired demographic data with scientific accuracy – just like marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett’s team found half a million fans of far-right groups across Europe and then encouraged them with adds, but instead of linking to a new band or diet product, the adds invited users to a survey asking about their level of education, their attitude towards violence, and the assessment of their own future.
Thanks to Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 supporters of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries – without even having to leave their offices once.
“It’s a fairly new research method,” Bartlett says.
Some of the results are hardly surprising. Online promoters of far-right groups are mostly young, male and annoyed about immigration.
But in a kind of surprising twist, “those who combine their online activism with an offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who stay behind their computer screens.”
DEMO’s work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new hot tool in the hands of scientists.
Idea factories, medical researchers, and political scientists use the site to study everything from health issues to societal trends such as likes, text messages, and status updates.
