"We have found a way to identify endangered children who otherwise would not have been found."
Facebook is also constantly tapping into the data of its own population.
The site’s data team has compiled statistics on relationship status and Valentine’s Day, voter turnout in the 2010 midterm elections, and a National Happiness Index (using primarily data that only Facebook has access to—masters of digital freedom have long known that the site should make its large data mine accessible to others for research purposes.)
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them whether they want to or not, and in order to be able to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, you allow the site to share your own personal information.
But what if Facebook users become part of a survey they don’t even know about?
While researchers have strictly defined guidelines on how to collect their data offline, everything is allowed online.
