He was certainly a designer, a dreamer, and a self-proclaimed hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer who was eager to craft diagrams—a man who believed that many executives suffer from “a disease of thinking,” “that a really great idea makes up 90 percent of the work... [but] there’s an enormous amount of craftsmanship between a great idea and a great product.”
In 1995, Bob Cringely developed the TV series "Triumph of the Idiots" about the break-up of the personal computer. And he sat with Jobs for more than an hour, in which they conducted one of the rare, in-depth conversations.
By that time, 10 years had passed since Jobs had been pushed out of Apple, and he was already working hard on his new computer company NeXT, looking forward to widespread adoption of the Internet.
While a small part of Cringley’s interview was used in specialist idiots, he says the interview’s copy templates were missing on delivery.
It was only after Job’s death that a full VHS copy was discovered in the director’s garage.
This slightly revised footage forms the basis for the 68-minute film "Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview," which will arrive at the Landmark Theatre this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to hate in-depth interviews, Jobs appears surprisingly eager to explain his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And incredibly thoughtful.
In the course of the interview, there are four long breaks between questions and answers – 10 to 15 seconds of reflection, in which jobs clearly weigh their thoughts and are striving for accuracy.
There are also moments when Jobs’ perfectionism comes to light when he seems impatiently responds to Cringely’s questions, pushing him to respond more quickly to topics or side actions of greater importance.
Recorded before the era of Pixar, iPod, or iPhone, the Lost Interview seems kind of terribly far-sighted when Jobs evaluates what other companies think is right or wrong and presents his own vision of the future of the computer.
It's one thing to read posthumous appreciations of Jobs' career, but seeing Jobs here as the eager dreamer on his way to greatness is something completely different, original and inspiring.
He has a vision of how things could and should be.
Shortly after he had done all this here, he left and did it.
A quick look at seven notable sequences of the Lost Interview:
How he learned to run a company:
"Throughout the years in business, I always ask, 'Why are you doing things?' And the answer you always get is, 'Oh, that's how it's done.'
No one knows why he does what he does. No one in the business really thinks deeply about things.
That's what I found.
Jobs continues his efforts to streamline accounting at Apple.
Astonished at how costs were recorded - usually starting with "standard costs" that were mere guesses and then adjusted with "deviation" - he developed an automated factory that ensured that business costs could be determined to the smallest.
How the Pope was enlightened:
Jobs talks about the "Blue Box" he built with Steve Wozniak, a device with which you could sneak into the telephone company and make long-distance calls for free.
