He describes how Wozniak and he would test the box by using a paid phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another while looping through as many satellites as possible.
"We sent stuff around the globe half a dozen times and when you yelled at the phone, it came out on the phone next door a minute later," Jobs said.
“We were young and we learned that we can build something ourselves that can control trillions of dollars in infrastructure around the world.”
We both didn’t know much, but we could build this little thing that can control a giant thing, that was an incredible lesson and I don’t think there would be Apple without them.
Jobs goes on to tell of a glorious prank Wozniak and he almost pulled off when they called the Vatican via Blue Box in the middle of the night to talk to the Pope, while they did their best to mimic Henry Kissinger.
Since several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak to the American diplomat, the two had to laugh before the pope himself came up on the phone.
How he fell in love with technology (and unpreparedly called Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, when he was looking for spare parts to build a frequency counter, he looked for Bill Hewlett in the phone book and called him.
Shortly after her 20-minute phone call, Jobs got a part-time job at Hewlett-Packard for the summer.
"That had a remarkable impact on me. It was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my views on what a company was and how well it treated its employees."
Later, Jobs became one of the HP employees who visited the company’s research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw “the first desktop computer ever manufactured.”
He was as big as a suitcase, had a small screen with a brown tube and I fell in love with him.
I would climb up at HP as a teenager and hang on to this machine and write programs for them.
How to Improve Innovation:
Several times in the interview, Jobs talks about how to invent new products spontaneously.
Early in his career, when he installed some boards, a customer asked him to assemble the entire computer.
He worked with a payment period of only 30 days and had to think through both the assembly and delivery of the finished equipment.
Later at Apple, he recalls the problems he had in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember breakthrough arguments... they screamed at me that it would take five years [to build a mouse that would cost $300] and I got up, went out and found a manufacturer."
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could build for $15. That was incredibly credible.
About large companies that are diminishing:
Long before resurrecting Apple, Jobs foresaw the ways in which so many industrial giants stumbled with their visions and lost control of their shares.
“Let’s say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make a better copyer or printer, then what?”
They own the stock monopoly, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing make it more successful, so [it’s such people] who ultimately run the businesses and the product that pushes people out of decision making.
The product genius that has led to this monopoly position is eradicated by the people who have no concept regarding good products vs. bad products - craftsmanship necessary.
This is what happened at Xerox.
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
It could have been 10 times bigger if it had been Microsoft in the 1990s.
You have captured the defeat of victory.
About innovation as an art form:
“There’s a lot of craftsmanship between a great idea and a great product... when you develop this great idea, it changes and grows.”
You learn a lot about your subtleties.
You have to make votings, certain things you can't, but electrons, glass, robots, factories.
You have to remember 5000 things, these concepts, and bring them all together...
Ultimately, it comes down to taste, it comes down to trying to deal with the best stuff that humans have created and then trying to bring those things together into what you do.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We are always shameless in stealing great ideas.
Part of what made Macintosh great was that the people who work there were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians who happen to be the best computer scientists in the world.
Had it not been for the computer industry, they would have created fantastic things in other areas.
