Climate adversities slowed down the economy
In the first year that Mario López Valdez is in government, unemployment and undeclared work rose in Sinaloa, while foreign investment declined and the economy stagnated.
2011 will be remembered in Sinaloa’s economic history. It is the first year that Mario López Valdez, who calls himself the initiator of change and fosters great hopes for economic growth, is in government. However, due to the climatic adversity, growth cannot be talked about, but, on the contrary, the main economic indicators deteriorated.
The low temperatures in February not only caused million-dollar losses in agriculture, but also placed tight limits on the growth of the state economy and caused a general decline in economic activity of 3.6 per cent in the first quarter. This is mainly due to the historical decline in agricultural development of 31.16 per cent, which slowed down on other economic sectors.
According to a report published by the Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Sustentable (Mexican Council for Sustainable Agricultural Development) on the impact of the frost, 582,000 hectares of agricultural land were damaged, of which 78.03 percent were completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07 percent were partially destroyed.
The decline in economic activity by November has led to a steady increase in unemployment in the Mexican state. The Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed a rapid increase in unemployment in the first quarter of the year, because from January to March, 55,053 inhabitants of Sinaloa had no employment, which corresponds to 4.53% of the working population. In the second quarter, the number of unemployed people rose from July to July.
Lower liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa this year is due to a number of factors. Economist Gerardo López Cervantes, Dean of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the University of Autónoma (UAS), comments, the policy of public institutions indirectly explains the growing unemployment.
"What we are currently observing is an increase in unemployment, which has to do with several factors, including losses in liquidity in the market as a result of the cuts in funding by the legislation passed in Congress to combat money laundering, because for those who are banned from accumulating dollars, it is not easy to get them to work for themselves, to invest them or to use them for anything else," he said.
Migration Stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that increasing unemployment is also a demographic factor.
"The number of people leaving the country in search of work abroad, especially in the United States, has declined. This is due to the problems of entry on the one hand and on the other because it is also difficult to find work there. These people stay here and are looking for work here, which increases unemployment," he says.
Black Labour
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious, considering the high proportion of undeclared work, which, according to INEGI, includes 60.38 percent of the workers in the country who work without paying into the social security funds.
Unemployment and undeclared work are the low wages, the lowest in all of Mexico, according to the statistics of the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social and the Secretaría del Trabajo y Previsión Social.
The average monthly income of workers in Sinaloa was 5,352 pesos by September, which is much less than the general government average, which is 7375 pesos.
Decline in ADI
In addition to the decline in economic activity and rising unemployment, 2011 saw the strongest decline in foreign direct investment (FDI) in the last decade. According to the Secretaría de Economía (State Economic Authority), the ADI was $630,597 from January to June, which represents a decrease of 87.74 percent compared to the $5,143,312 in the same period of the previous year.
For its part, the Secretaría de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno (Governmental Authority for Economic Development) recorded a total investment of 17 280,000 pesos in 2011, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
The debt
In view of the economic crisis, the state government applied for a loan of 3 000 000 000 pesos at the National Congress in July, which was to be invested in infrastructure projects to reactivate the economy in the 18 municipalities. The state congress approved an amount of 200 600 000 pesos, but no positive effects of the debt on any of the industries in the country could be detected until November.
Reactions
For the representatives of the entrepreneurship, the first year of government made Mario López Valdés’ inability to rule obvious.
Miguel Loredo López, chairman of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación, said that in 2011 no efforts were made to harmonize the views of different sectors, including the state government.
"The economic activity in Sinaloa was really very poor this year. It needs to be worked hard to regain the terrain lost this year and in 2012 we need to make a double effort. The efforts of all, and in particular the progress of the already well coordinated government team, have not been sufficiently coordinated," he said.
Slow economic development
Loredo López stated that events such as the frost at the beginning of the year made the country’s economic development difficult and slowed down.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including the frost. One of the most important impacts is a slowed economy that is not moving enough to produce an economic dynamic that could generate a decent flow of processes, products and services, so we will close the year well below our expectations," he said.
Redefining vocation
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, chairman of the Confederación Patronal de la República Mexicana in Sinaloa, said the state had to be encouraged to engage in more dynamic productive activities.
"In general, we have observed that work has been done. We believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program to redefine the economic vocation and line of the country, because it is important to activate all the material and human resources of Sinaloa," he said.
There is a lot to do
The chairman of Coparmex stressed the importance of developing a future perspective that guides the government’s efforts in a better way.
"In general, I would say that the government has achieved good results in various areas. Economic development has progressed, but it is important to develop a long-term program," he explained.
He stressed that the current state power has made progress with the government.
"There are areas in which one can say that the government has acted more comprehensively. What I can say is that it has worked and that the government is aware that a lot of work is still ahead of it," he said.
