In his contribution, the Prime Minister stated that he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the country government may not regulate with general rules the measures that the public administration is to take.
"I also do not believe that doing so would affect the independence of the regulator", she also recalled that the central government is responsible for planning strategic policy areas, such as the telecommunications sector, for constitutional reasons, because it is the central government that manages state affairs.
Replacing analog signals with digital is one of the most important changes that has taken place around the world in recent years, and it brings about a better use of the radioelectric spectrum, an increased quality of the signal and more channels.
The postponement of the transition, she said, was a postponement of the enjoyment of digitization, which is a decision in the public interest that has not only technical aspects, "because it covers economic, social, political and security aspects."
These matters, she stressed, "make the action of the entire system necessary, according to the principle of economic governance by the state, they included a group of features that put the Constitution into the hands of the central government."
She recalled that many countries around the world had already made the digital transition through the government, even though they had highly specialized facilities.
It cannot be concluded that the government would intervene in the powers of Congress by issuing the contested decree, because the laws passed by the legislature would be complied with," she assured.
