The quintet included Costa Rica in its tour to celebrate its 20th anniversary
"Playing in Costa Rica is a dream come true"
In the exclusive conversation with Viva, bassist Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam says the band is prepared to give one of their best concerts next Sunday at the National Stadium.
For more than 20 years they were expected, but the band assured that a dream came true for them when they played in Costa Rica.
This was assured by bassist and co-founder of the group, Jeff Ament, who gave Viva an exclusive interview from Brazil last week.
The band is in the South American part of their tour to celebrate their 20th anniversary and on Sunday, the 20th, they will make their only stop in Central America.
On this day, they will perform at the National Stadium at 7:30 p.m. together with the band The X from Los Angeles and Las Robertas from Costa Rica.
They read an excerpt from the conversation, whose full transcript can be found in the online edition of La Nación.
For your Costa Rican fans, a dream comes true when Pearl Jam plays in Costa Rica: Are you aware of what that means for your fans?
Playing in Costa Rica is a dream come true for us.
This is just the second time we’ve played in South and Central America, and so far it’s been great.
I have only been once to Costa Rica for a holiday. It is such a beautiful country that we will definitely stay there for a few more days.
It’s exciting to bring our music there.
I ask you this because the fans of the band are completely devoted, they experience the days before the concert most intensely.
What do you say to your most enthusiastic fans?
Thank you for being at our side all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica. Thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry to have taken so long to get here.
Some people even think that your concert will be the biggest show of the year.
Isn’t that a bit of pressure from your visit?
Some of the greatest shows we’ve done in the last 21 years have taken place in the last two weeks.
We played on some giant shows in Sao Paulo and we hope that they have made us fit for this concert in Costa Rica.
Really, we want to play there.
We love this country, we love surfing and we love the jungle, Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you get to know Costa Rica and its waves for surfing?
Many of our friends are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo where the waves are simply unimaginable.
My friends have always gone surfing to Costa Rica and Nicaragua. Together with Mexico, these are excellent areas for surfing. In this way, we have learned about people who love surfing.
With a look at the tour you have offered giant shows with many songs.
What are your plans for the event in Costa Rica?
Since we have never played there, we have no limits.
We will try to give the best possible show with a lot of different songs. We want to play a few songs from each album and offer our fans a good and versatile repertoire.
You never repeat your repertoire.
Why? Why?
I think that’s partly because we have nine records and we can play over 120 songs, and each likes a different song, so it’s not easy to decide which one we’re going to play.
If we include two or three songs that we haven’t played in a long time, we can better maintain our concentration and they surprise us because they remind us of the reasons why we liked these songs, otherwise they could be forgotten.
That makes the show more interesting for us, and I think that’s why it’s so interesting for the audience.
With this tour, you celebrate your twenty years of history.
When you look back, do you find it hard to believe in your success?
Yeah, totally.
First of all, I don’t think any of us ever imagined playing in a great rock band for more than 20 years, and that sounds like a dream.
We also continue to rely on this blessing and find it great to be able to make music together even now.
We like each other and are excited to produce music.
We are lucky to be able to drive to the places in the world that we have always wanted to visit.
Things couldn't stand better.
What did it mean for you to have actively participated in the birth of grunge?
It has always been an honor to be part of this group of big bands.
We are good friends with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising and abundantly unusual when a movement emerges from a group of friends.
From time to time, a band comes out of a city, but it is already unusual for five or ten groups to come from the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle Group.
Sometimes we still play together.
Last year we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and in Canada with Mudhoney and we saw Soundgarden on their tour. We are still happy to be friends with them all and it honors us to be part of this emerging Seattle sound.
It’s also very unusual for a band like yours to have stayed with the same musicians for so long.
Yes, four of us have been playing together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which alone is much more time than many bands can endure.
First of all, I believe that we all appreciate being happy to be still alive and, moreover, we take care of each other.
We are all close friends, which is why musical paths have opened up that give everyone the freedom to experiment.
One person knows the other and his music, and we couldn't be better off.
Your relationship with fame has not always been easy, but on the other hand, your success has allowed you to always do what you wanted.
How do you find a balance?
The way we have grown has made it easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure not to be on tour too often, because it’s too easy to fall for this game with huge crowds who love your music.
As long as you keep in mind that people came because of the music, it reminds you that you have to pay attention to the music and what it created, without being obsessed with being a famous rock star.
What memories do you have of your other project Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote very good songs and it was great in the beginning.
For three years we were a band that had never released a record until the death of Andy (Andrew Woods).
We were disappointed to have taken so long. We are still good friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore) who built the band with us. When I listen to a song or see photos, I think of what an incredible person Andy was and how he made me laugh. It was always a pleasure to go to work and talk about other topics of football and laughing together.
He was an extraordinary person and we miss him.
The national band Las Robertas are responsible for the opening of the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know her work, especially Eddie Vedder, and have chosen the band for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos of several groups and we liked this band the best, so we’re curious to see what Las Robertas can offer live. That’s sure to be exciting.
Why do you always change the lyrics of Yellow Ledbetter when you play live?
This is a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), I have no idea.
He sings it, and I think he sings the first thing that comes to his mind.
Who influenced you as a bass player?
of so many+
The first to come to mind are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk all afternoon about the bassists I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep the grunge alive, even though it is no longer a fashion item?
I don’t think we all feel very connected to the word grunge.
When I think about it, I think about the bands I mentioned before, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and everyone else who came up at the same time. If they are still important today, I think that’s great because it’s worth listening to this music and bands like Mudhoney are making better music now than ever before.
Initially her music was darker, now she is more positive.
Why? Why?
That’s interesting, because I think there are a few songs on the new album that might seem a bit lighthearted, but there are also other songs like The End or Just Breathe that are classified as very dark songs, although they also have something positive in them.
The tears came to both of them when I heard Ed playing them. They are very dark songs.
I think when you get older and something traumatic has happened in your life -- like losing a family member or a friend -- that affects your artistic work and your music, and these two songs clearly embody that for me.
But I also believe that you can be a happy person and still make dark music.
