Fujimori returned to hospital for medical examinations
Former President Alberto Fujimori was admitted to a public hospital on Tuesday to investigate the muscle loss of his legs, his family doctor informed.
The 72-year-old Fujimori, who served 25 years in prison for violating human rights during his reign (1990-2000), has several diseases, including tongue cancer, which has been operated on four times and is under control.
Alejandro Aguinaga, Congressman and his personal doctor, told TV that Fujimori was being examined for three days at the Peruvian Instituto Nacional de Enfermedades Neoplásicas hospital to determine the reason for his pain and muscle loss in the lower limbs.
Aguinaga commented that, in his opinion, Fujimori could be pardoned for humanitarian reasons, yet he did not wish to do so because he considers him innocent.
He was operated on four times for tongue cancer and lost 18 kilos of weight, along with other conditions such as severe erosive gastritis, a cyst in the pancreas, kidney stones, high blood pressure and blood circulation problems in the legs, the doctor listed.
Fujimori has been in the National Detention Centre for Special Operations of the Police since September 2007.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the killing of 25 people by the death squad of the Peruvian army, which was secretly active during his reign.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political relations
An official delegation, led by Uruguayan President José Mujica and made up of several ministers and entrepreneurs, will start their visit to Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two countries and discuss political issues of the region.
Mujica will meet next Wednesday with his Mexican counterpart Felipe Calderón, which, according to the president of Uruguay, will be the culmination of his full schedule with politicians, businessmen and a meeting with the collective of Uruguayans living in Mexico.
The meeting of both presidents in the city of Guadalajara "is suitable for exchanging information on all policy areas between the two countries," the South American country's presidential office announced on its website.
According to local media, Mujica is seeking Calderón’s support regarding the incident with France when French Prime Minister Nicolas Sarkozy placed the South American country on a list of tax havens at the G20 summit in the French city of Cannes.
In his discourse, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that are still acting as tax havens, which was rejected by Uruguay and prompted a request from his ambassador to the European country.
Mexico has chaired the G20 since November, a group of the world’s most powerful emerging and industrialized countries, and since January this year an agreement has been in place on the exchange of tax information to avoid double taxation with the South American country.
In recent years, the government of Uruguay has tried to accelerate the concretisation of tax information exchange agreements to be removed from the "grey list" of the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), according to countries that have not introduced all international standards for tax cooperation.
On a business level, there has been a free trade agreement between Mexico and Uruguay since 2004, which has contributed to a growing exchange of goods between the two countries.
The mustache installer enters the third dimension with "Super Mario 3D Land"
Super Mario has been fighting tirelessly for 25 years to save Princess Peach from the clutches of the evil Bowser, but so far never in three dimensions: in "Super Mario 3D Land" he fights for the girl's love in stereo technology.
The game, which is coming to store counters around the world this month, has been tailored from the very beginning to the features of the portable console Ninth 3DS, which can be played three-dimensionally without any special glasses.
“Mario is the character who has to tell how the stereoscope works without glasses,” said Omar <0xC3><0x81>lvarez, who is responsible for the press specialized in Nintendo in Spain at the presentation of the video game in Madrid.
<0xC3><0x81>lvarez explained that "Super Mario 3D Land" is "Nintendo's first video game to be developed for this console from the very beginning" because hit articles like "Star Fox 64 3D" or "Zelda: Ocarine of time 3D" have so far been adaptations of existing titles.
Nintendo’s spokesman underlined that, although it is three-dimensional, “Super Mario 3D Land” is an “affordable” video game that allows for a fast, fluid gameplay.
<0xC3><0x81>lvarez confirmed that "Super Mario 3D Land" contained two games in one: the first part is "light" to catch the less clever users.
After that, the experts can "turn a second round" about the different levels of the game, which are becoming increasingly difficult.
