Colom guarantees extradition of Portillos to the United States
Guatemalan President <0xC3><0x81>lvaro Colom announced on Tuesday that he would grant the extradition of former Governor Alfonso Portillo to be held accountable in the United States for the $70 million money laundering conspiracy.
The process on the US request for Portillo’s extradition ends so that it can be brought to justice.
In a press conference, Colom confirmed that his decision was based on the independence of the judiciary and the government, taking into account that a decision-making court had already ordered extradition.
He stressed that during his administration he did not interfere in court decisions and accepted all extradition requests that he was informed of.
Apart from Portillo, Sergio Ruano Marroquín is extradited for murder and serious bodily injury, Edgar Estrada Morales and Víctor Estrada Paredes, both for drug trafficking.
Colom's action is a governmental act that takes place when all judicial and constitutional instances of condemnation of the former President of the State (2000-2004) have been exhausted.
According to the decisions of the Fifth Criminal Court and the Constitutional Court of Guatemala, Portillo must be extradited once his legal situation in Guatemala has been clarified and his human rights are guaranteed.
