Trinijove helped 6,000 young people at risk of social exclusion
The organization was created to avoid the marginalization of young people without vocational training.
The first 25 years of the social welfare organization Trinijove have led to important results: During this quarter of century, 6,000 young people at risk of social exclusion were supported in order to find a way out of their difficult situation.
In addition, there are over a hundred jobs created for this social group.
On the occasion of the anniversary, an account was drawn yesterday at an event in the former factory buildings of Fabra i Coats, in which more than 300 people participated.
Trinijove was founded in 1986 in the Trinitat Vella district with the aim of helping young people with low education, without work, with drug problems threatened by the risk of marginality.
Yesterday’s celebration in Sant Andreu was attended by numerous leaders of institutions and institutions that have worked with the association over the past 25 years.
The participation of political representatives of different directions during campaign times proved the impartiality of the work done by Trinijove.
In addition to the President of the Generalitat (Parliament of the Autonomous Region of Catalonia), Artur Mas, and his predecessor Jordi Pujol participated in the celebrations of the former Socialist Minister of Education Ernest Maragall and the former mayor and current left-green city councillor Ricard Goma.
The large hall of Fabra i Coats was also visited by the current Catalan Minister of Social Affairs and Family, Josep Lluís Cleries, and the Director General of the Social Work of the Sparkasse La Caixa, Jaume Lanaspa.
Mas emphasized that Trinijove was created in very difficult times and that today's times are no less complicated, but he added that the work done so far "is a good foundation".
For the President of the Generalitat, Trinijove is an example who knows how to fight against difficult circumstances and gives hope to people in difficulty.
"The economic crisis is nothing new for the club and the work it does," he said.
Occupied house where giant parties were held was cleared
The homeowners had occupied 11 of the 13 apartments in the building at Balmes No. 51 (Barcelona).
The 12 house occupiers left the building yesterday afternoon without any resistance.
Everything indicates that the nightmares of the neighbors of the house No. 51 on Balmes street have come to an end.
Twelve people voluntarily left the building yesterday at noon, which they illegally occupied and in which they had organized huge festivals that had driven the neighborhood to despair. The eviction was carried out on judicial order without police intervention.
After the evacuation, the door lock was replaced to avoid a similar situation.
"From now on, access will be controlled," the house administrator confirmed.
The house occupiers, who had occupied 11 of the 13 apartments of the building - the rest were inhabited - took the entire electrical system and part of the water supply, and they had painted the walls and left behind all kinds of garbage, especially cans of alcoholic beverages.
In the three lower floors, huge parties were celebrated that lasted up to two days, driving the tenants to despair.
Next to the building is a nightclub, Balmes 51, which also suffered damage from it.
Their owner, Maria Pantinat, explained to Europa Press that their business had declined by 80% since the start of the house occupation.
The owner of the discotheque pointed out that the homeowners were doing their unfair competition, because they sold the drinks for three euros, while these cost 10 euros in the discotheque.
In addition, the owner of the recreational venue had been reported by the neighbors for rest disturbance, while, according to her statement, the noise did not come from the visitors of the disco, but from the occupiers and especially from the guests of the festivals that were organized there, and which, according to the statements of the angry neighbors, were becoming more and more prolonged in recent weeks.
The manager of the discotheque explained that the harassment had been so great that it agreed with the owner of the building to have no rent to pay for the last nine months.
The Guardia Urbana (urban police) also confirmed that it had received more complaints from the neighbors in the last few weeks.
Last week, the leader of the PP (Partido Popular - People's Party) in the City Council of Barcelona, Alberto Fernández Díaz, called for the building to be cleaned immediately and to get to grips with the problems of civic coexistence as well as the downturn of the neighborhood.
He explained that before the summer, only one floor of the building had been occupied, but that in recent months the house occupiers had penetrated into all floors of the building and almost all apartments.
In that sense, he added that "it is necessary to put an end to impunity and to take action against the anti-social actions in the building."
