After hearing the authorized representative of the betting house about 3.50 p.m., Larrazabal Bretón was immediately set free.
The court secretary, Jorge Yánez, drove to the San Nicolás de los Garza Municipal Prison to inform Jonás that he had been acquitted and his case would be placed in the file.
He also informed him of the court order for immediate release.
Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome announced details of the plane crash in which Secretary of State Francisco Blake and seven other people were killed.
The Secretaría de Comunicaciones y Transportes - SCT informed that the findings of the investigation into the accident in which the government secretary Francisco Blake Mora and seven other people died indicate that the helicopter, with its entire undamaged structure, hit the ground directly without the pilot could have an emergency landing.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary for Communications and Transport, mentioned that the pilot had confirmed before take-off that the weather conditions were suitable for the flight.
"The fact that the propeller wing had contact with trees at a height of 25 meters, with the helicopter losing the hull, seems to indicate that the helicopter had had several ground contacts."
He also explained that the helicopter was built for 19 occupants, which is why it met all the requirements for the transport of the personnel.
In addition, he said that during the investigations in the area where the machine had fallen, no helicopter parts were found.
"During the search, no aircraft parts were found elsewhere, the surcharge affected the entire structure.
The helicopter was built for 19 occupants, which is why it met all the requirements for passenger transport.
The area has an inclination of 7 to 30 degrees.
Currently, it is a priority to get the results as soon as possible, but it could take several months, perhaps even a year.
For his part, Gilberto López Meyer, Director General of Aeropuertos y Servicios Auxiliares (Mexican Secretariat for Aircraft and Auxiliary Services) assured that the helicopter from the Estado Mayor Presidencial had flown at travel speed and the aircraft had fallen on a soft slope.
"This information reinforces the assumption that it was a normal flight operation at the time of the impact."
At a press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six relevant points to be taken into account in the investigation:
Visible flight:
In accordance with the flight standards, it was a flight according to the rules of visual flight, which means that the crew should have had sufficient visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
The AICM recorded suitable weather conditions at take-off, with some deep-hanging clouds rising as it continued to fly towards the border area between Mexico City and the State of Mexico.
Selected routes:
It is possible that the team had chosen a lower area with better visibility towards the Cuernavaca Valley because of the clouds.
Impact point:
The collision coordinates and the last radar record of the helicopter match, and there may not have been any loss of control of the aircraft or any deviation from the flight route prior to the impact.
Scattering the remains of the aircraft in a limited area:
The information available to date indicates that the helicopter was impacted from a straight and lateral direction.
The pattern of scattered aircraft remains suggests that the helicopter with its undamaged structure hit the ground.
No evidence of fire or explosion:
The remains of the aircraft at the scene of the accident do not indicate a fire or explosion.
The latest investigation results indicate several ground contacts.
On-site investigations have found aircraft parts at an altitude of 9,200 feet above sea level, the terrain is sloping and has an inclination of seven to thirty degrees.
The photos show the sequence in which the helicopter probably broke.
Some information suggests that the helicopter may have had several ground contacts.
After a minute search in an area beyond the locked area at the accident site, no scattered aircraft parts could be found, reinforcing the assumption that the undamaged aircraft structure had bounced to the ground.
MSS Announces a Research Protocol to Find the Gene for Obesity
The Social Security Institute of Mexico is conducting a research project on finding the gene for obesity in children and adolescents, supported by IPN specialists.
The Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social - IMSS (Social Insurance Institution of Mexico) announced that it is conducting a research project on the discovery of the gene for obesity in children and adolescents under the title "Genetics of obesity in childhood and adolescence", which aims to find the genetic markers associated with obesity.
Miguel Cruz López, head of the Unidad de Investigación Médica en Bioquímica at the Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI, explained that an interdisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was set up.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students at the Instituto Nacional de Salud Pública (INSP) and the Centro de Investigación y de Estudios Avanzados (Cinvestav) del Instituto Politécnico Nacional (IPN).
The population is invited to participate in the study. Interested parties can come to the sports courts of the IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where tests with children and adolescents are conducted every Saturday from 8.00 am.
He stressed that the investigation began at the sports field of Cuauhtémoc (in the west of the state of México) and will continue since 8 October at the sports field of Nezahualcóyolt (in the east of the state of México).
When the target of 500 to 600 subjects has been reached, the study will be continued at the Independencia sports field (in the south of the capital district) and completed at Morelos (in the north of the capital district).
He explained that the aim of the study was to get to know the factors and the role of genetics in connection with the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and adolescents for the prevention of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the World Diabetes Day, he stated that it was aimed at completing nutritional questionnaires for three thousand children and adolescents aged six to 14 years with the consent and supervision of their parents.
They will also be asked questions about their physical activity and family history to control risk factors that could lead to diabetes or kidney failure.
He also explained that on the mentioned Saturdays, the subjects were measured (weight, size, waist circumference), their blood pressure was controlled and blood values such as glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetic factors (trying to identify genes associated with childhood obesity) were determined.
Cruz López stressed that this investigation would be conducted in response to health care professionals’ concerns about the alarming weight gain of young people.
"The health surveys from 1999 and 2006 showed that in almost six years the proportion of obese boys increased by 77 percent and that of girls with obesity by 47 percent, and that obesity also increased dramatically," the IMSS specialist said.
He stated that the search for genetic markers was justified because the genetic history of the population of Mexico was different from that of other peoples.
