UNAM asphalt prevents impact holes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the Mexican University of UNAM, develops modified asphalt with polymers to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If paid attention to the signs emanating from the road surface, it would not be necessary to completely repair almost 200,000 punch holes when the rainy season in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México erupts, said Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at the University of UNAM, warning and assuring the number of punch holes to be reduced considerably.
In his lecture “Technical Holes” on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory he is responsible for is developing polymer-modified asphalts to produce a mixture similar to asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera believed that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behavior of road surfaces and thus avoid the appearance of impact holes.
He explained that the asphalt - the heaviest part of oil - is a hydrocarbon compound, one of which has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalts - and the other part a low - the so-called malthenes. Together they give the road surface its characteristic toughness behavior.
Tough-elastic behavior of the asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180° C. At 120° C. it is very viscous and at 50° C. it is almost solid, while it becomes brittle at very low temperatures.
"This means that the resistance of the asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes in one day depending on weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," the chemical engineer said.
The researcher of the FQ noted that the streets of Mexico City had mostly a flexible road surface, composed of six layers of material, the last three of which included asphalt.
Between the top layers lies a wear layer of asphalt, which consists of small stones bathed in asphalt and then solidified.
Every single stone of this wear layer had been bathed in asphalt.
When the vehicles move on and forces are generated, this layer allows for a good distribution of forces in the road surface.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would be even better distributed," said the chemical engineer.
"Above the wear layer," he explained, "a final layer is laid, the so-called support layer, which consists of tiny stones, i.e. of sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
Since this layer is in contact with the vehicle tires, they require a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and it must produce friction.
As this road surface receives and distributes the most forces, the support layer also needs an appropriate thickness and the material it is made of must be maintained.
Weather conditions, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other important factors to consider, especially water," he said, "because it significantly affects the behavior of the wear layer.
When the terrain becomes damp, water penetrates into the layer and is difficult to expel, causing a softening of all layers of road surface and, as a result, the appearance of bump holes.
If a punch hole occurs," he said, "the top layer is first removed, while the wear layer is only affected afterwards. But the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that should be maintained by appropriate maintenance programs at the first signs."
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores stated that the vehicle load is another important cause of the occurrence of impact holes, so the thickness of each layer of road surface must always be proportional to the vehicle load and it must be ensured that this regulation is complied with in order to avoid frequent impact holes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there was still a lot of research to be done, for example on asphalt emulsions, which are already on the market in other countries, and with which the impact holes could be repaired easily and without the application of high temperatures.
