So was the work of the doctor who identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A lophoscopist from Cali went into history as the man who identified "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials plays a key role.
Last November, a lophoscopist from the Cali Prosecutor’s Unit of Investigation (CTI) came in as the man who confirmed the identity of the leader of the FARC (Fuerzas Armadas Revolucionarias de Colombia) by comparing the fingerprints: “Alfonso Cano”.
Of the seven lophoscopists in the CTI department, this week Eliazar González, a Puerto Tejada man who has been involved in criminal investigations for 21 years, had been on standby this week.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in Chocó communities, where he often had to go to the jungle for five days to reach the place where the bodies were to be identified.
In 2000, he moved to Valle and after completing the required courses he specialized in lophoscopy, which is the examination of the skin that is subjected to friction, i.e. the palms of the hands and feet.
During the week of the operation against the so-called Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was advised to pack clothes for at least three days.
Something great awaited him.
Friday night he flew in a helicopter from Palmira to Cauca.
He knew that he was to identify two bodies, and that there was a suspicion that one could be the man who had led the oldest guerrilla in the world, so he was to take with him the ten-finger imprint of Guillermo León Sáenz (his actual name).
However, when he reached the place where the body was, he was unable to identify it because of its physical appearance, because it was not in the least similar to the pictures he had seen in the mass media.
He had no beard, was dressed like a farmer in the area, wore no glasses, and was much thinner.
But fingerprints don't lie.
Armed with a magnifying glass, ink, a planter and a flashlight, Eliazar compared the body’s fingerprints to those on the print sheet.
He had seen it right: it was "Alfonso Cano".
The same night, this Puerto Tejada-born man was responsible for telling the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that he was actually the head of the FARC.
In search of traces
For a dactyloscope from Sijín in Cali, the tribute given to President Juan Manuel Santos Eliazar González at a press conference on the deployment against "Cano" was very important.
Many people do not know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science with no error rate, which can be a key factor in resolving a crime.
Lophoscopists not only identify bodies, they also support investigations into murder and robbery cases and confirm the identity of the people arrested.
At the time of their arrest, many offenders present false ID documents or they have none.
We'll take their fingerprints and search them in the database.
The researcher told us that in the event of a theft, he had to tear a piece of wall out of a house, because the thief had supported himself with his hand exactly at this point when he pulled out a safe filled with jewelry and money.
"Walls are difficult because their surfaces are unsuitable for fingerprinting, but in this case we were able to take the whole hand print and identify the offender who had participated in several thefts," he recalled.
Fingerprints can also be used to relieve or burden suspects of murder.
Recently, a dead person was found surrounded by bottles of alcohol.
In the investigation, it was suspected that a family member might be suspected, and in fact a fingerprint on the bottle matched.
Although this does not guarantee that it is the murderer, it is linked to the place where the crime was committed.
A CTI dactyloscopist explained that "the fingerprints would be taken from the object with chemical or physical reagents."
When they appear, a planter or ribbon is used to take them with you.
After that, the prints are sent to Asif, which is the criminal database, or to the civil registry office.
“The problem is that there are still many Colombians without identity papers,” the expert from the CTI explained.
He said that not everything is the way it was portrayed in the TV series SCI.
Just as not everything that shines is gold, not everything you touch is a fingerprint.
But it can still be used if you make a corresponding comparison.
