Energy policy:
Facts should win over dogmas
If there is an issue that cannot be dealt with on the basis of short-term considerations or on the basis of emotions, this is certainly energy policy.
Availability and costs of electricity directly affect the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is reasonable to take an election meeting as the occasion to reflect on this issue and on the position of nuclear energy.
The debate will only bear fruit if it examines the overall economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French should base their opinions on objective facts, rational data.
Although there are 7 billion people on this planet, demographic evolution is driving a doubling of electricity demand by 2050, and a huge proportion of the world’s population should not have to do without a vital element.
At the same time, it is necessary to mitigate the scarcity of fossil resources in order to continue to produce electricity continuously, without forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions, a topic that has disappeared from the ecological debate, in order to fight against climatic irregularities.
The Fukushima accident did not change any of these parameters.
Therefore, Germany remains isolated in its decision to renounce nuclear power.
This is not the case in Belgium, which subjects its decision to the need to find a substitute source, nor in Switzerland, which intends to build only nuclear power plants of the last generation.
The UK, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name just a few countries, continue to pursue their projects with determination.
The United States, for its part, has decided after Fukushima to join another unit of its park by re-opening the Three Mile Island plant, which was shut down after the nuclear accident.
Even if the German model, which focuses on renewable energy sources, is sometimes set as an example, reality contradicts the discourse.
The election in Berlin will take the form of an increase in electricity prices, an increase in CO2 emissions from gas and coal-fired power plants, an increase in energy dependence, particularly on Russia, which is enhanced by the increased use of import gas.
The totality of these unpleasant effects will become noticeable within a few months.
The case of Denmark gives cause for reflection.
On the one hand, Denmark is the European leader in wind energy, from which it draws 30% of its electricity, on the other hand, it is one of the strongest users of coal and gas, used alternately with wind energy; as a result, its CO2 emissions and its electricity price are 65% and 50% higher each than the corresponding European average.
Thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill than our French households.
Given that the energy price plays a key role in the globalised economy in terms of competitiveness and stability of industry on a national level, French companies have an advantage because of the cheapest electricity available in Europe.
Any significant reduction in nuclear power would, therefore, result in a sharp increase in energy prices, making the noble statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of purchasing power an illusion.
Surveys showed that this is a price that the vast majority of French people are not willing to pay as much as it shows resistance to the principle of this energy source.
We realize that our country’s energy policy has enabled us to build an industry with 125.00 direct and 410,000 induced jobs.
Due to its strong export character, it brings a multitude of specialized small and medium-sized companies to international markets and makes them the creators of countless jobs.
If France decides to withdraw from nuclear power, most of these SMEs will fall victim to it, and the annual <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>6 billion in investment goods and nuclear energy exports will shrink more and more.
Which electrician would commission an EPR designed to function for sixty years if the decline of its producer is pre-programmed?
