The low-carbon solutions developed by Areva for the use of nuclear power and renewable energy testify to the complementarity of energy sources.
Maintaining the highest possible level of safety is an absolute imperative for nuclear power.
In France, we have a security authority that carries out uncompromising and transparent controls in existing plants such as the construction in Flamanville.
Their work teams, which have made a name for themselves due to their professionalism, are just too obsessed with the idea of safety.
Within 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious incidents.
Only one, and in Three Mile Island, has entered under normal operating conditions, thus proceeding without consequences for humans and the environment.
In Chernobyl, the drama was sworn up by reactor construction and inexcusable human failure.
At Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident was caused by two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude that caused the deaths of several tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn its lessons from this accident just as it did from the previous two.
As a result of this approach, as well as the cooperation of the security authorities of the French and German operators and designers of nuclear power plants, the EPR presents a draft that enables it to be resistant to such phenomena.
