Restricting immigration would weaken growth and harm the labour market situation.
Fears about the influence of migrants are based on the notion that they threaten to substitute the domestic workers, especially the less qualified, by exerting pressure on their wages.
However, experience shows that immigrants are in fact much more complementary than local wage workers, as they focus on occupations in sectors that are technically unloaded in the workplace.
The low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that irritate local wage workers, the more qualified among immigrants work in dynamic sectors where education is not aligned with the job offer.
Positive wage effect
Just as a surgeon would find it difficult to work in a country where there is a shortage of anesthesiologists, this complementarity between locals and migrants also has a positive effect on wages and the domestic labour market situation.
In this way, Giovanni Peri calculated that a 1% increase in the flood of immigrants would result in a co-related, long-term increase in real wages between 0.6% and 0.9%.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity of ideas brought in by immigrants is beneficial to economic growth (high proportion of naturalized immigrants among American Nobel laureates; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants also contribute net to social welfare systems, on average around 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The World Labour Organisation estimates, for example, that a person who immigrates to Germany at the age of 30 makes a net contribution (income minus expenditure) of around 150,000 euros to the public budget on average over his lifetime.
Nicolas Sarkozy wished to bring about the missing intersections "with the teeth" at the beginning of his mandate.
These said teeth, which were supposed to deter immigrants, however, achieved exactly the opposite effect.
Europe has invented democracy, now it remains to think through European democracy
Democracy is a valuable asset; it is also a delicate asset.
The European continent should be able to remember itself who, after its invention in Athens more than two thousand years ago, had suffered the whole 20th century over the tragedies of the First World War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the Gulag, but also Francos in Spain, Salazar in Portugal and the supreme in Greece.
Some would have thought it sufficient to exercise the right to vote, in the most direct way possible, to see democracy conquer its enemies once and for all.
It has been known since Napoleon that it was a characteristic of the mindset.
The universal suffrage, which is the necessary condition of democracy, is not a sufficient condition for this and can just as well become the "instrument of oppression" as the Republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot put it then.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, separation and control of powers, an education, enlightenment, economic and social community spirit, a jurisprudence.
The crisis in Europe that we are in is an economic crisis, but it is just as much, and above all, a political and democratic crisis.
The change of mind in the Greek true-false referendum would have had a double revealing character in this respect: on the one hand that of the need for a powerful return of politics, but on the other hand that of the disturbing feeling of its impossibility, its inappropriateness.
This ambivalence should be considered obsolete.
The truth is that the front lines of democratic struggle have shifted today, and the Republican soldiers, or at least most of them, are no longer aiming in the right direction.
We have nothing to gain to push for a success of the national referendum, which was organised according to necessities and in the wrong order.
A free pass for the European sovereign or a leap with closed eyes into the void of nationalist retreat: a great choice for the citizen!
No, we want Hackebeil, but a collective task, fully justified, clarified and steady, an election and democracy, this time at European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain and Portugal - by the way, you don't know where to end the list - because there is only one crisis, and it is prevailing in Europe.
It is the whole of Europe that succumbs to the dictates of markets and rating agencies, which suffers from its impotence and lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that is humiliated at the international level.
One is concerned about transfers of sovereignty to Europe - it is the whole of Europe that is gradually losing its sovereignty, and thus each of the nations that are affiliated to it.
The urgency is to restore the leadership of the European project to the sovereignty of the people.
It is a question of whether Europeans can reduce the burden of their debt, free themselves from the markets and build a future through investment.
The exit from the crisis is conditional on decisions at European level that cannot be taken without total democratic legitimacy, without certainly ruining us.
After this proposal has been fought for a long time by Jacques Delors and the Socialists, everyone is now pushing European economic management to do so.
Agreed.
But imagine this without political integration and a stronger democracy - as it envisions the citizens - would be another folly and another cul-de-sac.
We need to take on a new stage in European construction.
In order to create the republic in France, it took the fact of "creating" Republicans.
The revolution of interests alone could not do enough here.
This instruction remains valid.
We need to build a more integrated Europe on an economic level.
This can only be achieved by creating a politically more democratic Europe, a truly European sovereignty of the people.
We need Europeans to create Europe.
"Contactless" smart cards become a common good
The World Chip Card Fair opens its doors on Tuesday in Villepinte near Paris in an optimistic stance.
According to Eurosmart, 2011 should actually end with an 11% increase in worldwide sales of microprocessor chips (EC cards, SIM card phone), with more than 6 billion units sold.
The most important segment is contactless technology, which allows payments in public transport or settlement of purchases by simply holding the card to a reader.
Compared to the 320 million sold a year earlier, 460 million contactless chip cards should be sold worldwide this year!
Their market share is expected to grow even further in 2012 (580 million expected units) and represent over 10% of the global chip card market (6,925 million cards).
Europe is gaining ground in terms of contactless payments after being behind the Asia-Pacific region for a long time.
Some 26 million Visa cards are already equipped with this functionality, and 75,000 payment terminals accept it.
In France, the beginnings are rather modest: only 400,000 contactless visa cards have been distributed.
Consumer markets, however, are making steam.
This year, Carrefour issued 2.5 million contactless pass MasterCards.
In order to move to a higher speed, it is now necessary that banks equip their customers with these cards.
"Two major French financial institutions have committed themselves to systematically handing out bank cards to their customers in the future, which are equipped with contactless chips," Gérard Nébouy, Director General of Visa Europe France, said in a statement.
Banks test payment via mobile phone
However, this is only a first step on the way to the payment method of the future: the mobile phone.
A very small percentage of devices have been equipped with the NFC (Near Field Communication) technology necessary to carry out these transactions.
"They've fallen into default".
"But they should at least experience a real upward trend next year."
"We expect to sell 80 to 120 million units worldwide in 2012," explains Marc Bertin, Chairman of Eurosmart.
But the banks are taking the initiative.
Crédit Agricole had announced yesterday the start of a test run in Caen, which will run from December to next June.
The iPhones of some 200 customers and employees will be equipped with a capsule that allows contactless payment.
The BPCE operates a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
Yesterday, Société Générale also announced that it was preparing to launch an offer that would enable its customers to make contactless payments via mobile phones.
