Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which runs on the seabed of the Baltic Sea and connects Western Europe directly to Russia, has been put into operation.
It will provide gas for an equivalent of 30 million households.
The Russian gas giant Gazprom wanted to celebrate this event with splendor and glory.
Over 500 invited guests, including four heads of state and government, attended the inauguration of the new gas transmission line Nord Stream, which connects Russia and Germany directly below sea level, on the Baltic Sea coast under orchestra sound and at the gourmet buffet on Tuesday.
German Chancellor Angelika Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have symbolically jointly turned the wheel of the valve that transports Russian gas to the Western European network.
With the new gas pipeline, 27.5 billion cubic meters of additional Russian gas per year will be delivered to Western Europe through a first pipeline of 1,224 km of length connecting the St. Petersburg region with Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania.
A second pipeline, allowing a total supply of 55 billion cubic meters of gas – the equivalent of French total consumption – is expected to be completed by the end of 2012.
And you already let the eventuality of the construction of a third line on its own track ring.
For Gazprom, the timely and precise completion of this enormous structure seems like a victory.
The project was highly controversial in Poland and the Baltic States.
The Nord-Stream pipeline will enable direct gas delivery to Germany, while avoiding any route through third countries (Poland or Ukraine) by land.
For this reason, these two countries are losing some of their power: for them, it is now becoming more difficult to put pressure on Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
Warsaw, most engaged in the debate, was not shy away from comparing the Nord-Stream pipeline with a "new German-Soviet pact" in connection with the alliance between Hitler and Stalin for the occupation of Poland in 1939.
This means that the issue is politically extremely sensitive.
Western Europe has gained even greater security of supply by supporting this Russian project.
However, this is at the expense of defusing European energy, as the project has broken a gap between Western and Eastern Europeans.
In barely five years, Russia has succeeded in enforcing its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich, Western countries, which have high gas consumption and whose gas reserves are declining.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us in an organic way," François Fillon confirmed at the inauguration of the gas pipeline, pointing out the extent to which the major gas contracts are also important from the political and economic side.
All this explains the broad smile of Gazprom’s managers, who are represented in Lubmin, regarding the gas supply line.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an outstanding technique.
The underwater pipe is made of steel with concrete sheathing, which is intended to protect it from ship anchorages.
It rests on the seabed, at about 200 m depth.
During their construction, minefields dating from World War II had to be avoided.
"About hundreds of mines had to be removed or destroyed for caution," said Jens Müller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
In addition, strengthened measures had to be taken to protect the fauna and flora.
The line is a long line of metal, heavy like 242 Eiffel towers, which is interrupted over the entire length by nothing: neither by valves, nor maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project managers distanced themselves from it, as the Swedes were not keen to see a Russian state company settle permanently at the level of their coasts.
"In the event of an accident, we close the gas passage in less than a minute," clarified Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas in the gas transmission line thus escapes into the air.
However, this case is considered unlikely by the designers, as the weld seams were estimated to have a leakage resistance per 100,000 years.
The state monitoring of the gas pipeline is ensured both by an underwater robot, which is controlled for external observation purposes from a seagoing ship, as well as by a device circulating inside the gas pipeline.
It has the shape of a cigar, measuring a meter in diameter, is inserted into the interior of the pipeline and moved through the gas pressure.
After three full days of moving through the line at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device provides the most accurate information on possible deformations of the metal upon arrival.
The gas pipeline was designed to function for fifty years without having to undergo the slightest repair.
The gas circulation is easily ensured by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the access point, 100 bar at the exit point.
Five companies have joined forces to realize this project.
However, the management remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
Furthermore, the German companies E. ON and BASF are affiliated here (each at 15.5%), as are the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (each at 9%).
These five companies have formed a business community called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased this company the entire capacity of its gas transport, on a renewable twenty-year contract.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how large the amount of gas that is actually transported," clarified Jens Müller.
The financing of the gas pipeline construction was backed by 30% of shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total labour costs for both pipelines should amount to 7.4 billion euros.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
However, the minority shareholders are prepared to recover their expenses, as Gazprom bears the liability risk alone.
The gas pipeline reveals itself on a sandy, pine-wooded coastline near Lubmin from the Baltic Sea.
The 4.5 meter high valves form the gas outlet gate.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other parameters of the incoming gas before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been supplied with one million cubic meters of Russian gas per passing hour.
At full capacity, this would be 3 million cubic meters per hour and 6 million in 2012.
Moleskine, a brand notebook.
Launched by an Italian company about fifteen years ago, Moleskine now wants to give writing a new style.
It has a flair of adventure, hours spent writing at candlelight.
Moleskine’s notebook is easily recognizable, with its black, rectangular cover, its rubber band, the eggshell-coloured sides, as aged over time.
However, the Moleskine notebook, as it is known today, was created in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, which is based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a distinguished design notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then a specialist consultant for the company, is commissioned with the launch of the new product.
The notebook was inspired by an old-fashioned production technique, called Mole Skin, which refers to a cotton coat used, for example, for covering upholstery benches.
This type of notebook was in great demand among writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has revived an old and almost forgotten item that was seen as an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century," explains Maria Sebregondi, now a brand manager at Modo Modo.
Success comes.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26%, establishing sales of 12.7 million units.
This is far from the usual production of the first years, when only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine crosses the Italian border and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to make a phantom image of the buyers, as the notebook is as enthusiastic as businessmen as well as students and professionals.
Moleskine has the image of cosmopolitan, cultivated and open-minded customers.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees in its beginnings, now employs more than 100 people and has two offices since 2008; one in Milan and the other in New York.
The company distributes its notebooks in bookshops, on internet portals such as Fnac, in small boutiques in city centers and knows how to assert its identity.
“We have followed the spirit of the time and his new writing needs, which exists despite the boom of emails,” explained Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural characteristic is accompanied by the development of the company Moleskine: recently, the brand launched an exhibition called "Detour", in which architects and artists exhibited their own notebooks.
In August, the company also launched a leopard-patterned cover at the Locarno Film Festival.
Moleskine benefited from its success and this cultural zeitgeist and knew how to diversify its products: bags, calendars, fillers, computer cases... The brand has the full range of articles.
In autumn 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, today Syntegra Capital, and opened a new chapter in the history of Moleskine.
Why does the unemployment rate of disabled workers remain at such a high level?
Approximately 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
Today begins the "15th Week of Work for the Disabled".
Despite a determined public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate of disabled people is always twice as high as the average: 19% against 9% of the total population.
Disheartening?
"No," stresses Éric Blanchet, Director General of the Adapt Association, which organizes the "Week of Work for the Disabled."
"The progress made within fifteen years is considerable."
At the time, the unemployment rate was not double, but three times higher.
"Nevertheless, there is still a great deal to do."
It must be said, however, that many obstacles continue to exist for disabled unemployed people before they get a job.
More often it affects the elderly: 37% are older than 50 years (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% of them do not have a high school diploma and there are only 10,000 disabled people among the 2.3 million students with a higher education degree.
Finally, long-term unemployment is also very widespread: 53% of the disabled versus 38% on average.
In short, there are so many criteria that make it difficult to re-enter work and that form the "core of the problem", says Christian Grapin, Director General of Tremplin, an association founded in 1992 that helps companies to recruit disabled workers.
So much for the factual brakes.
The unspoken remains, the attitudes that, although certain, are slowly evolving.
A study conducted in April by the association IMS-Entreprendre for the magazine La Cité stated that the managers surveyed had "a weak level of knowledge regarding disabled people" that was "overrepresented" by "persons in wheelchairs, mentally or intellectually disadvantaged".
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees still have a long way to go to achieve the employment target of 6% disabled workers set out in a 1987 law.
These latter figures, dating from 2008, refer to a quotient of 2.6%.
"We are now at around 3%," reports Pierre Blanc, Director General of Agefiph, the organization commissioned to collect contributions from companies that disregard this law.
Proof: The number of "paid" permanent establishments has decreased, as has the sum of the amounts paid between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which provides for increases in contributions, created a strong pressure on companies," Pierre Blanc said.
"But this improvement also expresses a real insight, especially among the large groups of companies."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of permanent establishments employ between 20 and 49 employees with disabilities, while companies with 100 to 199 employees employ 82%.
